The paper is primarily focused on communication complexity, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that studies the amount of communication required to solve computational problems. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also covers topics such as data structures, linear sketches, and sublinear-time algorithms, which are typically studied in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper discusses techniques for proving lower bounds, which are often studied in cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper touches on some applications of communication complexity, such as compressive sensing and linear programming, which are studied in cs.LG (Machine Learning).
